{"title_page": "Aguinaldo Jaime", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name         = Aguinaldo Jaime\n| image        = \n| office       = CEO of the Angolan Insurance Regulation and Supervision Agency\n| term_start   = 2017\n| term_end     = \n| predecessor  = Position established\n| successor    = \n| office1      = Foreign Investment Office Director\n| term_start1  = 1989\n| term_end1    = 1990\n| predecessor1 = Position established\n| successor1   = Maria Lu\u00edsa Abrantes\n| office2      = Minister of Finance\n| term_start2  = 1990\n| term_end2    = 1992\n| predecessor2 = Augusto Teixeira de Matos\n| successor2   = M\u00e1rio Alc\u00e2ntara Monteiro\n| office3      = Governor of the National Bank of Angola\n| term_start3  = 1999\n| term_end3    = 2002\n| predecessor3 = Sebasti\u00e3o Lavrador\n| successor3   = Amadeu Maur\u00edcio\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1954|1|15}}\n| birth_place  = Luanda, Angola \n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| birthname    = \n| citizenship  = \n| nationality  = Angolan\n| party        = [[MPLA]]\n| otherparty   = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| relations    = \n| children     = \n| website      = \n}}\n\n'''Aguinaldo Jaime''' (born January 15, 1954) is an [[Angola]]n political figure and economist. He served as [[Minister of Finance]] from June 1990 to April 1992,<ref>[http://www.minfin.gv.ao/docs/dspHistoria_B2.htm Minist\u00e9rio das Finan\u00e7as - Hist\u00f3ria] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531155300/http://www.minfin.gv.ao/docs/dspHistoria_B2.htm |date=May 31, 2011 }}</ref> President of the [[African Investment Bank]] (beginning in 1996), and as Central Bank Governor from 1999 to 2002. He was subsequently Deputy Prime Minister. He is also alumnus of [[London School of Economics]].<!--when?-->\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080328065747/http://www.angola.org/government.html Angola.org]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\n  title=[[Minister of Finance (Angola)|Minister of Finance]] |\n  before=[[Augusto Teixeira Jorge de Matos]]|\n  after=[[M\u00e1rio de Alc\u00e2ntara Monteiro]]|\n  years=1990&ndash;1992|\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Government ministers in Angola}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jaime, Aguinaldo}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Angolan economists]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Finance ministers of Angola]]\n[[Category:Governors of the Bank of Angola]]\n\n\n{{Angola-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name         = Aguinaldo Jaime\n| image        = \n| office       = CEO of the Angolan Insurance Regulation and Supervision Agency\n| term_start   = 2017\n| term_end     = \n| predecessor  = Position established\n| successor    = \n| office1      = Foreign Investment Office Director\n| term_start1  = 1989\n| term_end1    = 1990\n| predecessor1 = Position established\n| successor1   = Maria Lu\u00edsa Abrantes\n| office2      = Minister of Finance\n| term_start2  = 1990\n| term_end2    = 1992\n| predecessor2 = Augusto Teixeira de Matos\n| successor2   = M\u00e1rio Alc\u00e2ntara Monteiro\n| office3      = Governor of the National Bank of Angola\n| term_start3  = 1999\n| term_end3    = 2002\n| predecessor3 = Sebasti\u00e3o Lavrador\n| successor3   = Amadeu Maur\u00edcio\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1954|1|15}}\n| birth_place  = Luanda, Angola \n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| birthname    = \n| citizenship  = \n| nationality  = Angolan\n| party        = [[MPLA]]\n| otherparty   = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| relations    = \n| children     = \n| website      = \n}}\n\n'''Aguinaldo Jaime''' (born January 15 1954) is an [[Angola]]n political figure and economist. He served as [[Minister of Finance]] from June 1990 to April 1992,<ref>[http://www.minfin.gv.ao/docs/dspHistoria_B2.htm Minist\u00e9rio das Finan\u00e7as - Hist\u00f3ria] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531155300/http://www.minfin.gv.ao/docs/dspHistoria_B2.htm |date=May 31, 2011 }}</ref> President of the [[African Investment Bank]] (beginning in 1996), and as Central Bank Governor from 1999 to 2002. He was subsequently Deputy Prime Minister. He is also alumnus of [[London School of Economics]].<!--when?-->\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080328065747/http://www.angola.org/government.html Angola.org]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\n  title=[[Minister of Finance (Angola)|Minister of Finance]] |\n  before=[[Augusto Teixeira Jorge de Matos]]|\n  after=[[M\u00e1rio de Alc\u00e2ntara Monteiro]]|\n  years=1990&ndash;1992|\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Government ministers in Angola}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jaime, Aguinaldo}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Angolan economists]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Finance ministers of Angola]]\n[[Category:Governors of the Bank of Angola]]\n\n{{Angola-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aguinaldo_Jaime"}
{"title_page": "The Big Everything", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n|name = The Big Everything\n|image = The Big Everything poster.jpg\n|caption = Original poster\n|director = [[Nicolas Bazz]]\n|producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ann Barrel]]\n* Nicolas Bazz\n* [[Yann Bazz]]}}|writer = {{Plainlist|\n* Nicolas Bazz\n* Yann Bazz}}|starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jauris Casanova]]\n* [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Seuzaret]]\n* Benjamin Boyer\n* [[Laure Gouget]]\n* [[Pierre-Alain de Garrigues]]}}\n|music = [[Christophe Jacquelin]]\n|cinematography = [[Jean-Philippe Bourdon]]\n|studio = [[Ombres Production]]\n|released = September 16, 2015\n|runtime = 127 minutes|country = France\n|language = French}}\n\n'''''The Big Everything''''' is a 2015 [[science fiction film]] directed by Nicolas Bazz.\n\n==Plot==\nIn exchange for a full pardon, Niels (Jauris Casanova) joins a group of scientists on a trip to a [[black hole]] 50 [[light year]]s from earth. Because of [[time dilation]], a hundred years will pass on Earth while they are away on their planned six-week journey. However, an accident pushes them even further into space, with no hope of ever returning to their former lives.\n\n== Cast ==\n* Jauris Casanova : Niels\n* [[:fr:H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Seuzaret|H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Seuzaret]] : Ariane\n* [[:fr:Benjamin Boyer|Benjamin Boyer]] : Sam\n* Laure Gouget : Lucie\n* [[:fr:Pierre-Alain de Garrigues|Pierre-Alain de Garrigues]] : Harry\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Production Design ===\n\nThe spaceship of the film is very obviously not [[Aerodynamics|aerodynamic]] as it is not made for planetary exploration. It flies through the [[Void (astronomy)|cosmic void]], not through air. In the void there is no resistance and therefore no need for aerodynamics. It is designed for only one purpose, says Nicolas Bazz, interstellar travel, as fast as physically possible.\n\n=== Visual Effects ===\n\nBefore the shoot even started, Nicolas Bazz  and Yann Bazz, the former as a producer and the latter as [[Visual effects supervisor|VFX supervisor]], made a pact. \"No more than a hundred [[Visual effects|VFX]] shots\". After a full day of shooting and trying to avoid the green screens as much as possible, Nicolas Bazz, as director this time, realized the risk of doing a claustrophobic movie. And so the Bazz brothers made a new pact: there will be as few VFX shots as possible... But not one less. 750 is what was needed to tell the story of those characters properly.\n\nThe main challenge of [[Chroma key|greenscreen]] shooting is neither technical (though it does take forever) nor financial (it's still less expensive than shooting in space). No, the main difficulty is in the acting. More specifically, the \u201c[[black hole]] gaze\u201d. Usually visual cues such as ping pong or tennis balls are used to focus the actor\u2019 eyes on their virtual partners.  But no tennis ball can do justice to the wonder, fear and humility such a spectacle should evoke. It takes a lot of discipline and imagination from the actors and absolute accuracy in the direction to pull off. The \"black hole gaze\" was the focus of many rehearsals, often up until a few seconds before shooting each of those shots.\n\nThe [[Directorial|director]], Nicolas Bazz is usually involved in scouting for locations, but scouting the universe behind a VFX artist's shoulder proved very frustrating. To maintain control over sets and vistas, he asked the VFX supervisor to create a director-friendly interface dubbed \u201cThe Universe Engine\u201d. \u201cSpace vistas creation\u201d is Nicolas Bazz\u2019 fifth credit on the film.\n\n== Science ==\n\n=== Black Holes ===\n\nThe [[Black holes in fiction|black holes]] of the film aren't holes and they aren't black. The filmmakers chose a very specific type of black holes called [[Microquasars]]. The black sphere at the center, also known as the event horizon, is only a part of the whole. The [[accretion disk]] is the sum of all the matter the horizon attracts in an ever-accelerating spiral, some of which gets ejected before falling into the horizon, in relativistic particle jets.\n\n=== Quasar alignment ===\n\nEven though The Big Everything is a [[Hard science fiction|Hard Sci-Fi]] movie, using as much real science as possible, some concepts had to be invented. One of those inventions is that [[quasar]] class black-holes are aligned with each other, creating a \"path\" in the universe. To the writer's surprise, it was revealed to be true in 2014, but for as yet unknown reasons. A year later during a public screening, an audience member from the [[Paris Observatory]] walked up to the filmmakers during the post-movie debate. He revealed that he and his team had just found out the actual reason for quasar alignment: [[Dark matter|Dark Matter]] threads that shape the Universe. The \"path\" invented for the film has been confirmed by reality.\n\n== Details ==\n* Original title: [[:fr:Le Grand Tout|Le Grand Tout]]\n* Directed by: Nicolas Bazz\n* Written by: Nicolas Bazz & Yann Bazz\n* Produced by: Ann Barrel, Nicolas Bazz & Yann Bazz\n* Music: Christophe Jacquelin\n* Cinematography: [[:fr:Jean-Philippe Bourdon|Jean-Philippe Bourdon]]\n* Set decoration: Christian Baquiast\n* Costume design: Fabienne Margolliet\n* Makeup department: Zo\u00eb vand der Waal\n* Country: {{Country|France}}\n* Genre: [[Science fiction|Science-Fiction]]\n* Running time: 127 minutes\n* Release dates:\n** {{Country|France}}: September 16; 2015\n\n== References ==\n# [http://rue89.nouvelobs.com/blog/science-friction/2016/01/03/uchronie-voyage-spatial-ado-superheros-coups-de-coeur-de-sf-235162 The Big Everything in the Top of 2015's movies] (fr) from [[Rue89]]\n# {{IMDb title|id = tt1754331}}\n# [http://rue89.nouvelobs.com/blog/science-friction/2015/09/22/le-grand-tout-un-voyage-spatial-fantastique-en-huis-clos-234974 \u00ab Le Grand Tout \u00bb, un voyage spatial fantastique en huis clos] from [[Rue89]]\n#[http://www.parismatch.com/Culture/Cinema/Le-Grand-Tout-ne-manque-de-rien-826567 \"Le Grand Tout\" a tout pour plaire] from [[Paris Match]]\n#[http://autourduciel.blog.lemonde.fr/2015/10/01/les-plus-beaux-rendez-vous-astronomiques-en-octobre/ Ciel \u00e0 voir] from [[Le Monde]]\n#[https://www.causette.fr/le-mag/lire-article/article-1283/le-grand-tout-de-nicolas-bazz.html Le Grand Tout de Nicolas Bazz] from [[:fr:Causette|Causette]]\n#[http://www.futura-sciences.com/magazines/espace/infos/actu/d/trous-noirs-grand-tout-road-movie-univers-einstein-59678/ Le Grand Tout : un road movie dans l'univers d'Einstein] from [[:fr:Futura-Sciences|Futura-Sciences]]\n#[http://www.lyonne.fr/yonne/actualite/pays/puisaye/2015/11/11/le-grand-tout-de-la-science-fiction-made-in-france-au-cinelux_11658419.html Le Grand Tout, de la science fiction made in France au Cin\u00e9lux] from [[:fr:L'Yonne r\u00e9publicaine|lyonne.fr]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Big Everything}}\n[[Category:French science fiction films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n|name = The Big Everything\n|image = The Big Everything poster.jpg\n|caption = Original poster\n|director = [[Nicolas Bazz]]\n|producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ann Barrel]]\n* Nicolas Bazz\n* [[Yann Bazz]]}}|writer = {{Plainlist|\n* Nicolas Bazz\n* Yann Bazz}}|starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jauris Casanova]]\n* [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Seuzaret]]\n* Benjamin Boyer\n* [[Laure Gouget]]\n* [[Pierre-Alain de Garrigues]]}}\n|music = [[Christophe Jacquelin]]\n|cinematography = [[Jean-Philippe Bourdon]]\n|studio = [[Ombres Production]]\n|released = September 16, 2015\n|runtime = 127 minutes|country = France\n|language = French}}\n\n'''''The Big Everything''''' is a 2015 [[science fiction film]] directed by Nicolas Bazz.\n\n==Plot==\nIn exchange for a full pardon, Niels (Jauris Casanova) joins a group of scientists on a trip to a [[black hole]] 50 [[light year]]s from earth. Because of [[time dilation]], a hundred years will pass on Earth while they are away on their planned six-week journey. However, an accident pushes them even further into space, with no hope of ever returning to their former lives.\n\n== Cast ==\n* Jauris Casanova : Niels\n* [[:fr:H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Seuzaret|H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Seuzaret]] : Ariane\n* [[:fr:Benjamin Boyer|Benjamin Boyer]] : Sam\n* Laure Gouget : Lucie\n* [[:fr:Pierre-Alain de Garrigues|Pierre-Alain de Garrigues]] : Harry\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Production Design ===\n\nThe spaceship of the film is very obviously not [[Aerodynamics|aerodynamic]] as it is not made for planetary exploration. It flies through the [[Void (astronomy)|cosmic void]], not through air. In the void there is no resistance and therefore no need for aerodynamics. It is designed for only one purpose, says Nicolas Bazz, interstellar travel, as fast as physically possible.\n\n=== Visual Effects ===\n\nBefore the shoot even started, Nicolas Bazz  and Yann Bazz, the former as a producer and the latter as [[Visual effects supervisor|VFX supervisor]], made a pact. \"No more than a hundred [[Visual effects|VFX]] shots\". After a full day of shooting and trying to avoid the green screens as much as possible, Nicolas Bazz, as director this time, realized the risk of doing a claustrophobic movie. And so the Bazz brothers made a new pact: there will be as few VFX shots as possible... But not one less. 750 is what was needed to tell the story of those characters properly.\n\nThe main challenge of [[Chroma key|greenscreen]] shooting is neither technical (though it does take forever) nor financial (it\u2019s still less expensive than shooting in space). No, the main difficulty is in the acting. More specifically, the \u201c[[black hole]] gaze\u201d. Usually visual cues such as ping pong or tennis balls are used to focus the actor\u2019 eyes on their virtual partners.  But no tennis ball can do justice to the wonder, fear and humility such a spectacle should evoke. It takes a lot of discipline and imagination from the actors and absolute accuracy in the direction to pull off. The \"black hole gaze\" was the focus of many rehearsals, often up until a few seconds before shooting each of those shots.\n\nThe [[Directorial|director]], Nicolas Bazz is usually involved in scouting for locations, but scouting the universe behind a VFX artist\u2019s shoulder proved very frustrating. To maintain control over sets and vistas, he asked the VFX supervisor to create a director-friendly interface dubbed \u201cThe Universe Engine\u201d. \u201cSpace vistas creation\u201d is Nicolas Bazz\u2019 fifth credit on the film.\n\n== Science ==\n\n=== Black Holes ===\n\nThe [[Black holes in fiction|black holes]] of the film aren't holes and they aren't black. The filmmakers chose a very specific type of black holes called [[Microquasars]]. The black sphere at the center, also known as the event horizon, is only a part of the whole. The [[accretion disk]] is the sum of all the matter the horizon attracts in an ever-accelerating spiral, some of which gets ejected before falling into the horizon, in relativistic particle jets.\n\n=== Quasar alignment ===\n\nEven though The Big Everything is a [[Hard science fiction|Hard Sci-Fi]] movie, using as much real science as possible, some concepts had to be invented. One of those inventions is that [[quasar]] class black-holes are aligned with each other, creating a \"path\" in the universe. To the writer\u2019s surprise, it was revealed to be true in 2014, but for as yet unknown reasons. A year later during a public screening, an audience member from the [[Paris Observatory]] walked up to the filmmakers during the post-movie debate. He revealed that he and his team had just found out the actual reason for quasar alignment: [[Dark matter|Dark Matter]] threads that shape the Universe. The \"path\" invented for the film has been confirmed by reality.\n\n== Details ==\n* Original title: [[:fr:Le Grand Tout|Le Grand Tout]]\n* Directed by: Nicolas Bazz\n* Written by: Nicolas Bazz & Yann Bazz\n* Produced by: Ann Barrel, Nicolas Bazz & Yann Bazz\n* Music: Christophe Jacquelin\n* Cinematography: [[:fr:Jean-Philippe Bourdon|Jean-Philippe Bourdon]]\n* Set decoration: Christian Baquiast\n* Costume design: Fabienne Margolliet\n* Makeup department: Zo\u00eb vand der Waal\n* Country: {{Country|France}}\n* Genre: [[Science fiction|Science-Fiction]]\n* Running time: 127 minutes\n* Release dates:\n** {{Country|France}}: September 16; 2015\n\n== References ==\n# [http://rue89.nouvelobs.com/blog/science-friction/2016/01/03/uchronie-voyage-spatial-ado-superheros-coups-de-coeur-de-sf-235162 The Big Everything in the Top of 2015's movies] (fr) from [[Rue89]]\n# {{IMDb title|id = tt1754331}}\n# [http://rue89.nouvelobs.com/blog/science-friction/2015/09/22/le-grand-tout-un-voyage-spatial-fantastique-en-huis-clos-234974 \u00ab Le Grand Tout \u00bb, un voyage spatial fantastique en huis clos] from [[Rue89]]\n#[http://www.parismatch.com/Culture/Cinema/Le-Grand-Tout-ne-manque-de-rien-826567 \"Le Grand Tout\" a tout pour plaire] from [[Paris Match]]\n#[http://autourduciel.blog.lemonde.fr/2015/10/01/les-plus-beaux-rendez-vous-astronomiques-en-octobre/ Ciel \u00e0 voir] from [[Le Monde]]\n#[https://www.causette.fr/le-mag/lire-article/article-1283/le-grand-tout-de-nicolas-bazz.html Le Grand Tout de Nicolas Bazz] from [[:fr:Causette|Causette]]\n#[http://www.futura-sciences.com/magazines/espace/infos/actu/d/trous-noirs-grand-tout-road-movie-univers-einstein-59678/ Le Grand Tout : un road movie dans l'univers d'Einstein] from [[:fr:Futura-Sciences|Futura-Sciences]]\n#[http://www.lyonne.fr/yonne/actualite/pays/puisaye/2015/11/11/le-grand-tout-de-la-science-fiction-made-in-france-au-cinelux_11658419.html Le Grand Tout, de la science fiction made in France au Cin\u00e9lux] from [[:fr:L'Yonne r\u00e9publicaine|lyonne.fr]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Big Everything}}\n[[Category:French science fiction films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction films]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: it\u2019s \u2192 it's, \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Big_Everything"}
{"title_page": "Karen (name)", "text_new": "\n\n{{Other uses|Karen (disambiguation){{!}}Karen}}\n'''Karen''' is a given name. Used by our Boss CJF in all sorts of phrases. Karen is a worldwide MEME. Also Karen is used to say \"OKIE KAREN\" when youre in doubt. In [[English language|English]], it is a feminine name derived from the name [[Catherine]], like other similar [[Germanic languages|Germanic language]] names. In [[Kurdistan]], [[Iran]] and [[Armenia]], however, it is a masculine name deriving from other non-Germanic languages. The name is also found in modern [[Africa]], as well as in [[Asia]].\n\n==English==\nKaren entered the English language from Danish, where it has been a short form of \"Katherine\" since medieval times.<ref name=\"Onomastics\">{{cite journal | url=https://repozitorij.ffos.hr/islandora/object/ffos:1830 | title=Onomastics as evidence of linguistic influence | author=Fijok, Ivana |year=2012}}</ref> It became popular in the English-speaking world in the 1940s. The name Karen was one of the top 10 names for girls born in the [[United States]] during the 1950s and 1960s, peaking as the third most popular girl's name in 1965.<ref>{{citation|last=Davidson|first=Andrew|url=http://www.nameplayground.com/Karen|title=Population Statistics for Karen|year=2007|publisher=nameplayground.com|location=Raleigh, NC}}</ref>\n\nVariants include Caja, Kaja (Danish), Caren, Caryn, Karena, Kaat,  Karin, Karyn. The name is used in the Danish, Arabic, Dutch, Hebrew, Norwegian, German and English languages.<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/name/karen-1 \u0412ehind the Name]</ref>\n\nSince the late 2010s, the name \"Karen\" had been used in a similar vein as \"[[Becky (slang)|Becky]]\", to refer to a busybody middle-aged woman making formal complaints about trivial activities.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/science-tech/internet/2018/01/karen-sharon-becky-and-chad-how-it-feels-when-your-name-becomes-meme|title=Karen, Sharon, Becky, and Chad: How it feels when your name becomes a meme|author=Amelia Tait|date=2018-01-24|magazine=New Statesman}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/lifestyle/2019/05/karen-how-one-meme-ruined-a-mother-s-favourite-baby-name.html|title='Karen': How one meme ruined a mother's favourite baby name|author=Lana Andelane|date=2019-05-30|publisher=Newshub}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.georgetakei.com/people-who-know-chads-karens-2639964007.html|title=People Who Know Chads And Karens Admit How They Feel About Their Names Becoming Insults|author=Thomas Dane|date=2019-08-23|publisher=GeorgeTakei.com}}</ref>\n\n==In Armenia, Iran and Kurdistan ==\n\nIn [[Armenia]], [[Iran]], and [[Kurdistan]] ''Karen'' is a common masculine given name.\n \nThe masculine given name ''Karen'' derived from the Persian name of [[House of Karen]] (or Caren), one of the [[Seven Parthian clans|seven aristocratic families]] of the Mads Empire (Medians- Medes), who settled in Western parts of Achaemenid Empire. Several Persian princes named Karen are known before and after the Islamic period. The Karen house ruled the [[Tabaristan]] region of Iran, which approximately corresponds to the current provinces of [[Gilan Province|Gilan]] state and [[Mazandaran Province|Mazandaran]]. Moreover, Karen means a brave (or a valorous) man in Persian.\n\nKar or car (\u06a9\u0627\u0631) means work or job in [[Persian language|Persian]] and Kurdish. En (\u06cc\u0646) is an archaic suffix, which acts similar to (ist) in English. Therefore, the literal meaning of the name is he who sees/gets the job done. The last son of Kaveh the Blacksmith was named Karen. Karen had lost 12 older brothers to the evil Emperor Zahak, but survived to see the end of a revolution initiated by his father. According to the legend in Ferdowsi's ''Shahnameh,'' Zahak was cursed with two snakes on his shoulders. Zahak was advised to feed the snakes using brains of young boys to keep the curse from growing. Kaveh managed to dismantle Zahak's reign and save his last son with the help of a Persian king.     \n\nIn [[Armenian language|Armenian]], ''Karen'' is also derived from the ancient Armenian masculine given name '''Kar'''. The masculine given name '''[[Garen (disambiguation)|Garen]]''' is a [[Western Armenian]] form of the [[Eastern Armenian]] ''Karen''.\n\nThe masculine given name ''Karen'' was mentioned by the prominent Armenian historian [[Movses Khorenatsi]] (ca. 410\u2013490s AD; Armenian: \u0544\u0578\u057e\u057d\u0565\u057d \u053d\u0578\u0580\u0565\u0576\u0561\u0581\u056b) in his book ''[[History of Armenia (book)|History of Armenia]]''.<ref>History of the Armenia by Movses Khorenatsi: Book_2_#28 and Book_2_#68</ref>\n\n''Karen'' can also be a surname.\n\n==In Asia==\nIn [[Asia]], ''Karen'' is a feminine given name. The name can be found in [[Japan]], and less commonly in such places as [[China]], [[Malaysia]] and [[Philippines]]\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===First name===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*[[Karen Aardal]] (born 1961), Norwegian and Dutch applied mathematician\n*[[Karen Ackerman]] (born 1951), American children's author\n*[[Karen Allen]] (born 1951), American actress\n*[[Karen Alexander (disambiguation)]], several people\n*[[Karen Anderson (writer)]] (born 1932), American fantasy writer\n*[[Karen Anderson (squash player)]] (born 1971), Jamaican squash player \n*[[Karen Anette Anti]] (born 1972), Norwegian Sami politician\n*[[Karen Armstrong]] (born 1944), British author on comparative religion\n*[[Karen Arthur]] (born 1941), American film director, producer, and actress\n*[[Karen Dianne Baldwin]] (born 1963), Miss Universe 1982\n*[[Karen Bernstein]] (born 1969), Canadian voice actress\n*[[Karen Bjornson]] (born 1952), American model\n*[[Karen Black]] (1939-2013), American actress\n*[[Karen Blixen]] (1885\u20131962), Danish author under the pen name Isak Dinesen\n*[[Karen Carlson]] (born 1944), American actress\n*[[Karen Carpenter]] (1950\u20131983), American singer and drummer\n*[[Karen Cashman]], American short track speed skater\n*[[Karen Cellini]] (born 1958), American actress\n*[[Karen Chen]], American figure skater\n*[[Karen Chin]], American paleontologist, coprolitologist, and taphonomist\n*[[Karen Clark-Sheard]] (born 1960), American gospel singer and songwriter, member of the ''Clark Sisters''\n*[[Karen Cockburn]] (born 1980), Canadian Olympic trampolinist\n*[[Karen Connelly]] (born 1969),  Canadian travel writer and novelist\n*[[Karen Crouse]], American journalist and author\n*[[Karen Daley]], president of the [[American Nurses Association]]\n*[[Karen David]] (born 1979/1980), Indian-Canadian actress\n*[[Karen Devine]], American computer scientist\n*[[Karen Dotrice]] (born 1955), English former actress\n*[[Karen Dunne]] (born 1967), American track and road cyclist\n*[[Karen Elson]] (born 1979), British model and singer\n*[[Karen Friedman]] (born 1946), wife of mobster Henry Hill, depicted in ''[[Goodfellas]]''\n*[[Karen Gillan]] (born 1987), Scottish actress\n* [[Karen L. Gould]] (born 1948) American scholar of French-Canadian literature, president of [[Brooklyn College]]\n*[[Karen Handel]] (born 1962), American politician\n*[[Karen Harding]] (born 1991), English singer\n*[[Karen Hassan]] (born 1981), Northern Irish actress\n*[[Karen Haude]], German field hockey player\n*[[Karen Horning]] (born 1966), Peruvian breaststroke swimmer\n*[[Karen Kain]] (born 1951), Canadian ballerina, currently artistic director of the National Ballet of Canada\n*[[Karen Kilgariff]] (born 1970), American comedian and podcast host\n*[[Karen Killilea]] (born 1940), subject of two books by her mother, Marie Killilea\n*[[Karen Kingsbury]] (born 1963), Christian fiction author\n*[[Karen King-Aribisala]], Nigerian writer\n*[[Karen Kohanowich]], former United States Navy diver\n*[[Karen Kotte]] (died 1509), Danish merchant\n*[[Karen Kurreck]] (born 1962), American road cyclist\n*[[Karen LaFace]] (born 1966), American diver\n*[[Karen Lancaume]] (